topic.title: NTB Memory Mapped Registers

strow.stentry: To describe the memory mapped registers used in NT communication and call out how to access them over GAS

body.p: NTB Memory Mapped Registers contain NT Information Register, NT Control Registers and NT Doorbell/Message Registers.
The NT Control Register Array contains an array of control registers for each partition. This allows a management processor to configure all of the NTBs from a single vEP.
The NT Doorbell/Message Registers also include 48 instances, one for each partition.

table.title: NTB Memory Mapped Registers

entry.p: NT 0 Doorbell & Message Registers / vEP 0 MSI-X Table & PBA
NT 1 Doorbell & Message Registers / vEP 1 MSI-X Table & PBA
NT 47 Doorbell & Message Registers / vEP 47 MSI-X Table & PBA

topic.title: NT Control Registers

body.p: The NT Control Registers provide an interface for a driver to setup NT Windows to translate address and ID. The overall layout of NT Control Register is shown below.

table.title: NTB Control Registers

row.entry: NT Requester ID Mapping Table Register Entry 0
NT Requester ID Mapping Table Register Entry 1
NT Requester ID Mapping Table Register Entry 511

body.p: The NT Control Header is used to determine the offset and count of the Address and ID Translation Configuration Registers, keep track of the status of recent Address and ID Translations entries, and to control the setting and locking of new Address and ID Translation values.

table.title: NT Control Header Layout

section.title: NT Partition Status Register
section.p: The NT Partition Status Register provides the lock status of the local partition.

table.title: NT Partition Status Register Field Description

entry.p: After the NT EP is initialized or the NT EP is reset, the NT state is placed into Operation Normal.
The RC can request to Lock the NT by writing the NT OPC to 0x1. At this point the NT State transitions to Lock In Progress state.

If resource allocation fails, the state switches back to Operation Normal state, otherwise, the state transitions to Operation Locked state. In this state, the RC can change NT settings by writing the NT Control Registers, and the RC can apply the changes by writing NT OPC to 0x2(Configure NT).

The NT State will switch to Configure In Progress state. If there is any error in the configuration, the NT state switches back to Operation Locked state. If there is no error, the configuration is applied into hardware and the NT state switches to Operation Normal state.
In Operation Normal and Operation Locked states, the RC can reset NT by writing NT OPC to 0x3 and the NT state will go back to Reset In Progress state.
After reset is completed, the NT state goes back to Operation Normal state. See #NTB_Memory_Mapped_Registers-2/fig_NT_Partition_State_Control_Transition_Di_9ipi0e7jb for a detailed state diagram.
This field indicates who has locked the local partition. Locked Partition ID is the ID of the partition where the RC locks the partition.

p.note: If Locked Partition ID is 0xFF, the partition is not locked and access to the NT Control registers will be accessible by any partition. If the partition is locked by one specific partition, accesses to NT Control Registers are allowed for that partition, but accesses from any other partitions are not allowed.

entry.p: When this bit is set, ID protection checking performed by the NT EP for posted request is disabled. If the requester ID is not hit in the ID Table, all posted requests regardless of requester ID are allowed to access NT Window and the requester ID should be replaced with the BDF of NT EP; The TLP is routed to PPU for error handling if this bit is not set and requester ID is not hit in the ID Table.
ID Protect Disable is not applicable for non-posted requests.
This field is valid only when ID PROT DIS is set.
If this bit is set, the No Snoop field of the NT request TLP of the corresponding requester is inverted. If this bit is cleared, the No Snoop field is kept unchanged.

topic.title: NT Doorbells and Message Registers

body.p: NT Doorbells and Message Registers are used to communicate between devices over an NT Interconnect. For example, as IPC between hosts residing in separate switch partitions connected through NTB. A doorbell event or message register can be sent from the source (outbound) partition to the destination (inbound) partition.

table.title: NT Doorbell and Message Register Layout

section.title: ODB (Outbound Doorbell)
section.p: ODB register is a 64-bit register, each bit corresponds to one outbound doorbell event.
Writing 1 to one ODB bit will ring the outbound doorbell event to the corresponding inbound doorbell in all other partitions. When writing 1 to one ODB bit, the bit will be auto-cleared.
The ODB register read always returns 0s.

section.title: ODBM (Outbound Doorbell Mask)
section.p: ODBM register is a 64-bit register, each bit is the mask bit for the corresponding bit in outbound doorbell register. Each bit is decoded as below:

When an outbound doorbell bit is masked (set to 0), the corresponding outbound doorbell is masked to ring out and the outbound event will not be propagated to the inbound doorbell register in other partitions.

section.title: IDB (Inbound Doorbell Status)
section.p: IDB is a 64-bit register. Each bit corresponds to one of the 64 inbound doorbells. A bit in IDB is set when the corresponding inbound partition doorbell bit is active. When one bit is set, write 1 to clear the status.

section.title: IDBM (Inbound Doorbell Interrupt Mask)
section.p: IDBM is a 64 bit register. Each bit in this field corresponds to one of the 64 inbound doorbells. When a bit in IDBM is set to 0, the corresponding bit in the inbound doorbell status register is masked from generating an interrupt(MSI or MSI-X).

section.title: IMAP (Inbound Doorbell Message Map)
section.p: IMAP is a 64-byte registers. Each IDB bit is associated with corresponding byte in IMAP. Each byte of IMAP defines the interrupt vector for inbound doorbell. For each byte in IMAP, only bit[5:0] are used, and bit[7:6] are reserved , thus the valid vector range is 0~63.
section.note: The maximal vector number is defined in Max Vector Number field of NTB Setting Block in Switch Configuration File. So the interrupt vector < Max Vector Number.

section.title: MMAP (Outbound Message Map)
section.p: MMAP is one 4-byte register. Each NT EP supports four Inbound Message (IMSG[3:0]) registers and four Outbound Message (OMSG[3:0]) registers. Each outbound message register in a partition is associated with corresponding byte of MMAP. When an outbound message register is written, the value written to the register is transferred to the inbound message register specified by lower 2-bit of MMAP, and the destination partition for inbound message is selected based on upper 6-bit of MMAP.

table.title: MMAP

section.title: Outbound Message
section.p: The layout of outbound message registers are shown as below:

table.title: Outbound Message Register

section.p: Writing a value to OMSGx updates the value in the Inbound Message (IMSG) selected by MMAP register.
Each OMSG has 1-bit outbound message status (OMSGS) which indicates empty/full status of OMSG. Message status bits are RW1C.

section.title: Inbound Message
section.p: The layout of inbound message registers are shown as below:

table.title: Inbound Message Register

section.p: Each destination partition has four 32-bit IMSG registers.OMSG value received is stored in IMSG register selected by MMAP register associated with the OMSG register. IMSG is a RO register.
Each IMSG is associated with one bit Inbound Message Status(IMSGS) which indicates empty/full status of IMSG. The status bit is RW1C.
Each IMSG is associated with one bit Inbound Message Interrupt Mask(IMSGM) which is used to mask interrupt generated when inbound message status is set. IMSGM is a RW register.

Each IMSG is associated with one bit Inbound Message Source Partition (IMSGP). This register indicates that from which source partition the outbound message has arrived into the inbound message register. IMSGP is a RO register.

section.title: MSI-X Table
section.p: The MSI-X vector registers are shown as below:

table.title: MSI-X Vector Register

section.p: System-specified message address. For MSI-X messages, the contents of this field from an MSI-X Table entry specifies the lower portion of the DWORD-aligned address (AD[31::02]) for the memory write transaction. This field is read/write. Modifying this field when the system is using the MSI interrupt may cause undefined behavior.
section.wintitle: Msg Upper Address (MSI-X Message Address, x=[63:32])
section.p: System-specified message upper address bits. If this field is zero, 3DW MMWr TLPs are used. If this field is non-zero, 4DW MMWr TLPs are used. This field is read/write. (Note: Modifying this field when the system is using the MSI interrupt may cause undefined behavior.)

System-specified message data. For MSI-X messages, the contents of this field from an MSI-X Table entry specifies the data driven on AD[31::00] during the memory write transaction's data phase. This field is read/write. Modifying this field when the system is using the MSI interrupt may cause undefined behavior.

When this bit is set, the function is prohibited from sending a message using this MSI-X Table entry. However, any other MSI-X Table entries programmed with the same vector will still be capable of sending an equivalent message unless they are also masked. This bit's state after reset is 1 (entry is masked). This bit is read/write.Modifying this field when the system is using the MSI interrupt may cause undefined behavior.

section.title: PBA
section.p: The PBA registers are shown as below:

table.title: PBA Register

section.p: For each Pending Bit that is set, the function has a pending message for the associated MSI-X Table entry. Pending bits that have no associated MSI-X Table entry are reserved. After reset, the state of reserved Pending bits must be 0. Software should never write, and should only read Pending Bits. If software writes to Pending Bits, the result is undefined. Each Pending Bit's state after reset is 0 (no message pending).
